                     <interp inst="t18200517-56-defend568" type="age" value="26"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
             was indicted for that <rs id="t18200517-56-off332" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18200517-56-off332" type="offenceCategory" value="royalOffences"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18200517-56-off332" type="offenceSubcategory" value="coiningOffences"></interp>
               he, on the <rs id="t18200517-56-cd333" type="crimeDate">6th of January</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18200517-56-off332 t18200517-56-cd333"></join>, at <placeName id="t18200517-56-crimeloc334">St. James, Clerkenwell</placeName>
                     <interp inst="t18200517-56-crimeloc334" type="placeName" value="St. James, Clerkenwell"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18200517-56-crimeloc334" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                     <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18200517-56-off332 t18200517-56-crimeloc334"></join>, feloniously did dispose of and put away a certain forged and counterfeit Bank note for payment of 10 l. (setting it forth, No. 1226, dated July 6, 1819, signed C. Watts) with intent to defraud the 
                     <persName id="t18200517-56-victim569" type="victimName">Governor and Company of the Bank of England<interp inst="t18200517-56-victim569" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                     </persName>
                  , he well knowing it to be forged and counterfeit
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>SECOND COUNT, the same, only calling the forged instrument a promissory note for payment of money instead of a Bank note.</p>
